  "prompt": "How did the real estate bubble burst in America?",
  "response": "The real estate bubble burst in America primarily due to the subprime mortgage crisis, which unfolded between 2007-2009. Here are the key factors:\n\n1. Lending practices\n- Banks offered mortgages to borrowers with poor credit\n- Low initial interest rates (adjustable-rate mortgages)\n- Minimal documentation requirements\n- Relaxed lending standards\n\n2. Housing market conditions\n- Rapid home price appreciation\n- Speculative real estate investing\n- Overvaluation of housing assets\n- Excessive housing construction\n\n3. Financial market dynamics\n- Mortgage-backed securities were widely traded\n- Complex financial instruments spread risk throughout the financial system\n- Credit rating agencies gave high ratings to risky securities\n\n4. Triggering events\n- Interest rates began rising\n- Adjustable-rate mortgages reset to higher rates\n- Many homeowners couldn't afford their mortgage payments\n- Foreclosure rates increased dramatically\n- Housing prices declined sharply\n\n5. Broader economic impact\n- Major financial institutions collapsed (e.g., Lehman Brothers)\n- Stock market crash\n- Global financial crisis\n- Severe economic recession\n\nThe combination of these factors led to the massive real estate bubble burst, causing significant economic disruption and long-lasting financial consequences.",
